# TypeScript: Type Alias vs Interface

Both `type` and `interface` can describe object shapes, but they have key differences that guide when to use each.

## Interface

Best for **defining object shapes and contracts**, especially when you expect them to be extended or implemented.

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

// вң… Declaration merging (auto-extends across files)
interface User {
  email: string;
}

// вң… Extends other interfaces
interface Admin extends User {
  role: string;
}

// вң… Classes can implement them
class AppUser implements User {
  name = "John";
  age = 30;
  email = "john@example.com";
}
```

## Type Alias

Best for **unions, intersections, tuples, primitives, and complex type expressions**.

```typescript
// вң… Union types (interfaces CAN'T do this)
type Status = "active" | "inactive" | "banned";
type Result = Success | Error;

// вң… Intersection types
type Admin = User & { role: string };

// вң… Tuples
type Coordinate = [number, number];

// вң… Mapped / conditional types
type Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };
type Nullable<T> = T | null;

// вң… Primitives & utility aliases
type ID = string | number;
```

## Quick Decision Guide

| Scenario | Use |
|---|---|
| Object shape / API contract | `interface` |
| Union or intersection types | `type` |
| Declaration merging needed (e.g., library augmentation) | `interface` |
| Tuples | `type` |
| Primitives / literal types | `type` |
| Mapped / conditional types | `type` |
| Class implementation contract | `interface` |
| Function signatures (standalone) | Either (both work) |

## Key Differences Summary

```typescript
// 1. Declaration merging вҖ” only interface
interface Window {
  myCustomProp: string; // merges with global Window
}

// 2. Union вҖ” only type
type Input = string | number; // interface can't do this

// 3. Computed properties вҖ” only type
type Keys = "x" | "y";
type Point = { [K in Keys]: number }; // { x: number; y: number }
```

## Rule of Thumb

> - Use **`interface`** for public APIs,

# Sequential `await` vs `Promise.all`

The key difference is **concurrency** вҖ” how the promises execute in relation to each other.

## Sequential `await`

```javascript
async function sequential() {
  const a = await fetchUser();    // Starts and waits (e.g., 2s)
  const b = await fetchOrders();  // Starts AFTER a finishes (e.g., 2s)
  // Total time: ~4s
}
```

- The second promise **doesn't start until the first resolves**
- Total time = sum of both durations

## `Promise.all`

```javascript
async function parallel() {
  const [a, b] = await Promise.all([
    fetchUser(),    // Starts immediately (e.g., 2s)
    fetchOrders()   // Starts immediately (e.g., 2s)
  ]);
  // Total time: ~2s
}
```

- Both promises start **at the same time**
- Total time = duration of the **slowest** one

## Visual Timeline

```
Sequential:
  fetchUser:   |в–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳ|
  fetchOrders:          |в–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳ|
  Total:       |================| ~4s

Promise.all:
  fetchUser:   |в–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳ|
  fetchOrders: |в–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳв–Ҳ|
  Total:       |========| ~2s
```

## Error Handling Differences

| Behavior | Sequential `await` | `Promise.all` |
|---|---|---|
| **First fails** | Stops immediately, second never runs | Both were started; rejects with first error |
| **Second fails** | Only happens if first succeeded | Rejects as soon as *any* promise rejects |
| **Both fail** | Only first error is thrown | First rejection is thrown; second is potentially an unhandled rejection |

```javascript
// Promise.all вҖ” fails fast
try {
  const [a, b] = await Promise.all([slow(), fast()]);
} catch (e) {
  // If fast() rejects first, you get that error immediately
  // slow() is still running but its result is ignored
}
```

## When to Use Which

- **`Promise.all`** вҖ” when the promises are **independent** (e.g., fetching unrelated data)
- **Sequential** вҖ” when the second depends on the first's result:

```javascript
const user = await fetchUser(id);
const orders = await fetchOrders(user.accountId); // needs user first
```

